featured_reviews.review_id: The mosque was built by Mirza Ghulam Murtaza, father of hazrat Mirza Ghulam Ahmad sahb, the founder of the Ahmadiyya movement, in 1876. The mosque had been renovated and extended repeatedly throughout the 20th century by the Ahmadiyya administration and the capacity of the building increased from its initial capacity of 200 to 15,000 by the year 2014. And 1 white minaret is situated here which you can see by entering the city.

featured_reviews.review_id: It is a holy place of ahmadiyyas. Built during the lifetime of Ahmadiyya jamaat founder Hazrat  Mirza Ghulam Ahmad Qadiani. Many alhaams took place in this mosque on Imam Mehdi Alehis Salaam. Very sacred place of worship for Ahmadis of the whole world. Five times prayer are held round the year and attended by the ahmadis residing in Qadian. During various events like Jalsa Salana in December , Saalana Ijtema in October and Majlis Shura in February the mosque is full to its capacity and many namaazis don't get apportunity to offer namaaz in this particular mosque because it is on first come first get apportunity to offer namaaz and it is bit small in size. Great place to offer namaaz.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Nicely kept, but despite huge investment, ironically maintained with thick carpets of frozen climate areas not in keeping with hot tropical climate of Indian Punjab. ACs are rarely used, carpets smell. Only good for 3 winter months, rest of the hot season, May to Sep. it's patience-testing to be there without ACs. The crowd of prespiring devotees quickly make for the exits as soon as the congregational prayers are over!
This is the condition of almost all the masjids locally in 8 months of hot season. Hence none from abroad visits this place in hot seasons.
